WEEK 1

Days 1–2
Introduction to OSINT

In this part, I will introduce what OSINT (Open-Source Intelligence) is and how it works. I will explain the difference between OSINT and other types of intelligence such as HUMINT and SIGINT. I will also discuss why OSINT is useful in cybersecurity, investigations, and research.

I will cover the legal and ethical rules we must follow when doing OSINT, and I will explain the difference between passive and active searching.

Activities may include searching public social media accounts, reviewing LinkedIn profiles, and gathering basic website information.

Days 3–4
OSINT Process

Here, I will explain the step-by-step OSINT process:

I plan what information I need.

I collect data from open sources.

I analyze the information.

I report my findings clearly.

I will also show how to check if sources are reliable, how to identify misinformation, and how to verify information using multiple sources.

Example activity: I will verify a public post by checking different websites and references.

Days 5–6
Finding Digital Footprints

In this section, I will explain what a digital footprint is and how information about a person or organization can appear online. I will introduce basic metadata concepts, such as hidden information inside photos or files.

I will practice searching usernames or emails and applying basic social media search techniques.

Tools I will try:
Google search
Google Dorks (basic operators)
Wayback Machine
HaveIBeenPwned

Example exercise: I will take a public username and try to find where it appears online.

WEEK 2

During Week 2, we will have intramurals, so there will be no academic sessions.

WEEK 3

During Week 3, we will focus on prelims, so there will be no academic sessions.

WEEK 4

Day 1
Advanced Search Techniques

I will practice advanced Google Dorks such as site:, filetype:, intitle:, and inurl:. I will learn how to find publicly available documents and search for specific file types like PDF, DOCX, and XLSX. I will also explore cached and archived pages.

Exercise: I will try to locate publicly available documents from a specific organization.

Day 2
Website and Infrastructure OSINT

I will learn the basics of domain investigation, including WHOIS lookup and DNS information gathering. I will explore basic subdomain discovery and identify website technologies.

Exercise: I will investigate a public website’s domain and technology stack.

Day 3
Image and Geolocation OSINT

I will practice reverse image searching and review basic EXIF metadata. I will learn how to identify landmarks and environmental clues to determine where a photo was taken.

Exercise: I will verify the location of a photo using open sources.

Day 4
Breach and Exposure Research

I will study how data breaches happen and how to check if an email address has been exposed in breach databases. I will learn about paste sites and public leaks, as well as the risks of password reuse.

Exercise: I will check a test email address for exposure.

Day 5
Social Media Deep Dive

I will conduct deeper profile analysis, track usernames across platforms, analyze timelines, and map basic networks of connections.

Exercise: I will map the public connections of a sample profile.

Day 6
Final Practical OSINT Mini Project

For the final project, I will choose a public target such as a company, fictional case, or public figure. I will define my objective and apply the full OSINT process:

I will plan what I need to find.
I will collect information from open sources.
I will analyze the data.
I will report my findings.

My final submission will include the objective, sources used, findings, verification steps, and ethical considerations.
